news_header: U.S. crude oil inventories rebounded by 3.5 million barrels last week, remaining 6% below the five-year average.
news_text: A report from the Energy Information Administration revealed that U.S. crude oil inventories increased by 3.5 million barrels for the week ending January 24th, following a decrease of 1.0 million barrels the previous week. Economists had predicted a rise of 3.7 million barrels. Current inventories stand at 415.1 million barrels, approximately 6% below the five-year average. Gasoline inventories also rose by 3.0 million barrels but are slightly below the five-year average. In contrast, distillate fuel inventories fell by 5.0 million barrels, about 9% below the five-year average.
